            "id": "2bff8b72adf94853a900a",
            "questionText": "During a live concert, sound engineers adjust settings to optimize the listening experience. If the sound waves propagate at a wave speed of $!$343\\,\\text{m/s}$!$ and a specific note has a frequency of $!$440\\,\\text{Hz}$!$, calculate the wavelength of this sound wave.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "4ff046539e794c629040a",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the fundamental relationship that connects wave speed, frequency, and wavelength. Please select the correct wave equation from the options below.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e2484863-f982-4229-94d2-b6df0b9b92ca"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = f\\lambda$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = v \\cdot f$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f = v/\\lambda$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "3b5d1bf5649249d080143",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, use the identified equation to express the wavelength in terms of wave speed and frequency. Which of the following rearranged formulas correctly represents the wavelength?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e2484863-f982-4229-94d2-b6df0b9b92ca"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = \\frac{v}{f}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = v \\cdot f$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = \\frac{f}{v}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "1135d314258342fcb6610",
                    "stepText": "Now that you have the correct rearranged formula, substitute the given values for wave speed ($!$343\\,\\text{m/s}$!$) and frequency ($!$440\\,\\text{Hz}$!$) into the formula. Calculate the numerical value for the wavelength.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.78"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e2484863-f982-4229-94d2-b6df0b9b92ca"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "834e8f915dc1435db9374",
            "questionText": "During a live concert, sound engineers work to prevent echoes by minimizing reflections off hard surfaces. Imagine a sound wave from a speaker hits a flat wall at an angle of incidence of $!$60^\\circ$!$. Calculate the angle of reflection.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "de4c86e68db44dfeabe2e",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the principle that relates the angle of incidence to the angle of reflection. Which relation correctly describes this principle?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "56c92c0a-9a1f-4b88-8b6b-8a7541f4d657"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\theta_i = \\theta_r$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\theta_i = 2\\theta_r$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
